<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="491" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,658,1007]" pageId="12" pageNumber="491">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,874,899]" pageId="12" pageNumber="491">Habitat.</emphasis>
Sandy-muddy or sandy-rubble bottoms, near coral reefs, sea grasses beds or mangroves, occasionally associated with gobies; intertidal to at least 
<quantity box="[821,865,910,935]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="491" unit="m" value="5.0">5 m</quantity>
deep.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="491" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,658,1007]" pageId="12" pageNumber="491">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,946,971]" pageId="12" pageNumber="491">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1798" box="[327,497,946,971]" class="Malacostraca" family="Alpheidae" genus="Alpheus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="12" pageNumber="491" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rapax">
<emphasis box="[327,497,946,971]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="491">Alpheus rapax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from related species by having a broader scaphocerite and shorter fingers of the minor chela (see Bruce, 1994).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
